<br>
I have tested my theory that manually opening the door will cause AOE to agro hub mobs based on Line of Sight.  My scenario above was a *real* experiment and not a scenario.<br>
<br>
However, I mistakingly assumed that every time Hub mobs killed a raid party it was because a PLAYER manually opened the door.  I never considered the fact that mobs could be agroed *without* the door being agroed, and thus open the door themselves to come in for a killing spree.<br>
<br>
I will have to say that from my previous test, the AOE seems to be more apt to hitting the hub mobs with the door open.  Now...there is one variable that my test was missing, and I need this covered, but its not convenient to test this on a whim.<br>
<br>
The variable is the proximity of the wandering hob mobs to the HoT door when the door is initially opened.  <br>
<br>
Here is what I'm trying to say, but as of right now I can provide on &quot;conjecture&quot;:  I'm suggesting that yes, mobs can be agroed through the door, and that the door does not directly block AoE damage.   If one of these wandering hub mobs was close enough to the door, it could catch the AE, open the door, and kill the party via the pathing problems described above.<br>
<br>
} = hub<br>
- = blank space<br>
P = Player<br>
* = hub mob<br>
| = HoT door<br>
<br>
}------*--|    May result in Agro, while:<br>
<br>
}--*------|    May not.<br>
<br>
}------*--|P   If player had been hit by AOE, and was now agro'ly KoS to CoV+'s friend, he may agro mob through door.<br>
<br>
But here's something I never thought of before, what if:<br>
<br>
}--*-----P|  What if this Allied player was hit by the AoE through the door just before opening it, and was not KoS due to CoV+'s friend hitting him.  Perhaps mob close to the hub would agro on him as he went through the door, dragging the hub mobs into the fray.  That would *really* make it seem like him opening the door caused this, when it reality it was approaching the door and being hit by the AoE that caused it.<br>
<br>
Just some more &quot;conjecture&quot; for someone to test,<br>
